{{Occupational hazards}}
'''Engineering controls''' are strategies designed to protect workers from [[Occupational hazard|hazardous conditions]] by placing a barrier between the worker and the hazard or by removing a hazardous substance through air [[Ventilation (architecture)|ventilation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/engcontrols/|title=NIOSH Directory of Engineering Controls|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=U.S. [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]]|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref><ref name="Roelofs2007">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-4lTEuFWtdIC&pg=PA9|title=Preventing Hazards at the Source|first=Cora|date=1 January 2007|publisher=[[American Industrial Hygiene Association]]|year=|isbn=978-1-931504-83-6|location=|pages=9ff|author=Roelofs}}</ref> Engineering controls involve a physical change to the workplace itself, rather than relying on workers' behavior or requiring workers to wear protective clothing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osha.gov/dte/grant_materials/fy10/sh-20839-10/hierarchy_of_controls.pdf|title=Hierarchy of Controls|last=|first=|date=|website=U.S. [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration]]|access-date=2017-03-09}}</ref>
Engineering controls is the third of five members of the [[hierarchy of hazard control]]s, which orders control strategies by their feasibility and effectiveness. Engineering controls are preferred over [[administrative controls]] and [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) because they are designed to remove the hazard at the source, before it comes in contact with the worker. Well-designed engineering controls can be highly effective in protecting workers and will typically be independent of worker interactions to provide this high level of protection. The initial cost of engineering controls can be higher than the cost of administrative controls or PPE, but over the longer term, operating costs are frequently lower, and in some instances, can provide a cost savings in other areas of the process.<ref name="CDC">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/topics/hierarchy/default.html|title=Hierarchy of Controls - NIOSH Workplace Safety and Health Topic|last=|first=|date=|website=U.S. National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-30}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>
[[Hazard elimination|Elimination]] and [[Hazard substitution|substitution]] are usually considered to be separate levels of hazard controls, but in some schemes they are categorized as types of engineering control.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsaa.ca/effective-representation/hazard-identification-elimination-and-control|title=Hazard Identification, Elimination and Control|last=|first=|date=|website=Health Sciences Association of Alberta|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314062833/https://www.hsaa.ca/effective-representation/hazard-identification-elimination-and-control|archive-date=2017-03-14|dead-url=yes|access-date=2017-03-13|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://machinerysafety101.com/2011/02/28/understanding-the-hierarchy-of-controls/|title=Understanding the Hierarchy of Controls|last=Nix|first=Doug|date=2011-02-28|website=Machinery Safety 101|access-date=2017-03-10}}</ref>
The U.S. [[National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health]] researches engineering control technologies, and provides information on their details and effectiveness in the NIOSH Engineering Controls Database.<ref name="CDC"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwwn.cdc.gov/niosh-ecd/|title=Engineering Controls Database|last=|first=|date=|website=U.S. National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426223139/https://wwwn.cdc.gov/niosh-ecd/|archive-date=2017-04-26|dead-url=yes|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref>
