{{Infobox person | name = Richard Urquhart Goode | image = Richard Urquhart Goode.jpg | caption = A photograph of Goode taken shortly before his death | birth_date = {{Birth date|1858|12|8}} | birth_place = [[Bedford, Virginia]], [[United States|U.S.]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1903|6|9|1858|12|8}} | death_place = [[Rockville, Maryland]], U.S. | nationality = American | occupation = [[Geologist]] | known_for = [[Goode Mountain]], [[United States Geological Survey]] }}
'''Richard Urquhart Goode''' (December 8, 1858 – June 9, 1903) was an [[United States|American]] [[geographer]]. He was born in [[Bedford, Virginia]]. He attended the [[University of Virginia]] before joining the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers|U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]] in 1877. In 1879, he became a [[topographer]] with the newly created [[United States Geological Survey]] where he worked until 1879. From 1882-1882, Goode was attached to the Northern [[First Transcontinental Railroad|Transcontinental Railroad Survey]] as an engineer and topographer. In 1884 he rejoined the USGS. In 1888, while on a leave of absence from the USGS, Goode served as an engineer and astronomer for the Panama Canal Company. In 1889, he rejoined the [[United States Geological Survey|Survey]] as a geographer and was placed in charge of surveys of the Pacific Coast states - [[California]], [[Oregon]], and [[Washington (state)|Washington]]. He served in that role until his death.<ref>{{cite news|title=Richard Goode's Funeral.: Service This Morning at St. Margaret's Episcopal Church.|work=Washington Post|issue=p. 7|date=June 11, 1903}}</ref>
Goode married Sophie J. Parks of Norfolk, Virginia in 1889. They had three children. He was a member of the [[Washington Academy of Sciences]], the [[National Geographic Society]], and the [[Cosmos Club]]. From 1901 to 1903, he was the chairman of the Committee on Technical Meetings at the [[National Geographic Society]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Richard Urquhard Goode|journal=National Geographic Magazine|date=January 1, 1903|volume=14|issue=November 1903|page=424-425}}</ref>
==Honors== * [[Goode Mountain]], the highest peak in North Cascades National Park and fourth highest in Chelan County, Washington is named after Mr. Goode<ref>[http://www.peakware.com/peaks.html?pk=2929 Peakware World Mountain Encyclopedia]</ref>
==Publications== * "[https://pubs.er.usgs.gov/usgspubs/pp/pp45 The geography and geology of Alaska : a summary of existing knowledge]" with Alfred Hulse Brooks and Cleveland Abbe. US Geological Survey Professional Paper No. 45, 1906. * ''The Idaho-Montana Boundary Line'' National Geographic Magazine. January, 1900, Vol. 11, No. 1. pages 23–28. * ''[https://pubs.er.usgs.gov/publication/b201 Results of primary triangulation and primary traverse, fiscal year 1901-2]'' US Geological Survey Bulletin No. 201, 1902 * ''[https://pubs.er.usgs.gov/publication/b185 Results of spirit-leveling, fiscal year 1900-1901]'' US Geological Survey Bulletin No. 185, 1901 * ''[https://pubs.er.usgs.gov/publication/b170 Survey of the boundary line between Idaho and Montana, from the international boundary to the crest of the Bitterroot Mountains]'' US Geological Survey Bulletin No. 170, 1900 * ''[https://archive.org/details/magneticdeclinat00goodrich Magnetic declination]'' (1899) * ''[https://archive.org/details/westvirginiageo00survgoog West Virginia Geological and Economic Survey: Reports]'' (1899)
